<paragraph blockId="4.[811,1456,1236,1517]" box="[813,903,1236,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">REMARK</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[811,1456,1236,1517]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
This species was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="POCOCK R. I." box="[1169,1342,1267,1294]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" pagination="357 - 368" refId="ref4726" refString="POCOCK R. I. 1897. - Report upon the Scorpiones and Pedipalpi obtained on the Lower Amazons by Messrs E. E. Austen and F. Pickard-Cambridge during the trip of Mr Siemens Steamship ' Faraday'. Annals and Magazine of Natural History 19: 357 - 368. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222939708680549" type="journal article" year="1897">Pocock (1897)</bibRefCitation>
from the region of Santarém in Brazilian Amazonia. Subsequently it proved to be largely distributed all over 
<collectingCountry box="[1282,1454,1331,1357]" name="French Guiana" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
and the Amazon region. It presents a very high polymorphism for some morphometric characters (
<bibRefCitation author="LOURENCO W. R." pageId="4" pageNumber="369" pagination="463 - 466" refId="ref4132" refString="LOURENCO W. R. 1988. - Diversite biologique et modalites de la speciation chez les Scorpions amazoniens; Tityus silvestris Pocock, un cas particulier de polymorphisme. Comptes rendus des seances de l'Academie des sciences, Ser. III, 306 (15): 463 - 466." type="journal article" year="1988">Lourenço 1988</bibRefCitation>
). It was recorded for several sites in 
<collectingCountry box="[1282,1455,1427,1453]" name="French Guiana" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="LOURENCO W. R." box="[851,1057,1459,1485]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" pagination="771 - 808" refId="ref4096" refString="LOURENCO W. R. 1983. - La faune des scorpions de Guyane francaise. Bulletin du Museum national d'Histoire naturelle, 4 e serie, 5 (3): 771 - 808." type="journal article" year="1983">Lourenço (1983)</bibRefCitation>
, but the record for the Mitaraka region is new.
</paragraph>
